\begin{definition}
Consider a general linear method $\mathcal{M}$ and a non-degenerate starting method $\mathcal{S}$. The method $\mathcal{M}$ has order $p$ relative to $\mathcal{S}$ if the results found from $\mathcal{S}\mathcal{M}$ and $\mathcal{E}\mathcal{S}$ agree to within $O(h^{p+1})$.
\end{definition}

context_latex:
\paragraph{Context}
The context involves analyzing the order of a general linear method $M$ when used with a starting method $S$. $S$ is defined by generalized Runge--Kutta methods, and non-degeneracy requires at least one $b_{0}^{(i)} \neq 0$. $SM$ and $ES$ are vectors of approximations whose Taylor expansions are compared to define order.

Variables:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $M$: a general linear method
    \item $S$: a starting method defined by generalized Runge--Kutta methods (530a) for $i = 1,2,\dots,r$
    \item $SM$: vector of results from carrying out a step of $M$ based on initial approximations computed using $S$
    \item $ES$: vector of approximations formed by advancing the exact solution forward a time step $h$ and then applying each member of $S$ to the result
    \item $p$: order of the method (a non-negative integer)
\end{itemize}

Referenced equations:
\begin{itemize}
    \item (530a): generalized Runge--Kutta methods defining the starting method $S$, with coefficients including $b_{0}^{(i)}$
\end{itemize}
